        {
          "scid": "thig5.3:1.0.3",
          "en": "3. Sīhā"
        },
        {
          "scid": "thig5.3:1.0.4",
          "en": "“Distracted, harassed by desires of sense, Unmindful of the ‘what’ and ‘why’ of things, Stung and inflated by the memories Of former days, o’er which I lacked control—"
        },
        {
          "scid": "thig5.3:1.0.5",
          "en": "Corrupting canker spreading o’er my heart— I followed heedless dreams of happiness, And got no even tenour to my mind, All given o’er to dalliance with sense."
        },
        {
          "scid": "thig5.3:1.0.6",
          "en": "So did I fare for seven weary years, In lean and sallow mis’ry of unrest. I, wretched, found no ease by day or night,"
        },
        {
          "scid": "thig5.3:1.0.7",
          "en": "So took a rope and plunged into the wood: ‘Better for me a friendly gallows-tree! I’ll live again the low life of the world.’"
        },
        {
          "scid": "thig5.3:1.0.8",
          "en": "Strong was the noose I made; and on a bough I bound the rope and flung it round my neck, When see! . . . my heart was set at liberty!”"
        }
      ],
